 The Blind Shar-Pei's Quest

  Verse 1
  There's a wrinkly little dog with a face like a prune,
  With eyes that have never seen the moon.
  A Shar-Pei so blind, he bumps into chairs,
  But his nose knows the way through the night air.
  With legs that look like toothpick sticks,
  He trots around giving everyone kiss.

  Chorus
  Oh, he's blind but he's following the scent,
  Of something that smells so incredibly mint.
  A Shar-Pei so silly, so wrinkled and sweet,
  On a mission he simply cannot defeat.

  Verse 2
  He waddles on past the old mailbox stand,
  With floppy brown ears and a paw in each hand.
  His owner says "Buster, where you going tonight?
  You're sniffing that bush with all of your might."
  But Buster just whines, with a determined huff,
  "That smell's calling to me, it's more than enough!"

  Chorus
  Oh, he's blind but he's following the scent,
  Of something that smells so incredibly mint.
  A Shar-Pei so silly, so wrinkled and sweet,
  On a mission he simply cannot defeat.

  Bridge
  With every step forward his wrinkles all shake,
  Like a bowl full of jelly, that's what people say.
  But he knows what he's doing, that nose never lies,
  Through the dark of the evening, under starlit skies.

  Verse 3
  He follows the trail past the neighbor's big fence,
  With his tongue hanging out, making no complaints.
  A hundred deep breaths, pulling scents from the ground,
  Until finally there, right in front of him, found—
  A giant trash can with the smell of pure joy,
  Leftover chicken from last night's roast boy!

  Outro
  So here's to the blind dog, the wrinkly detective,
  Who smells like a dream and acts like a protectant.
  A Shar-Pei with purpose, so silly and grand,
  The snootiest sniffer in all of the land.